.TH SHIT 1 "2026-06-15" "shit" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
shit \- a fast POSIX and bash compatible shell
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B shit
.RI [ options ]
.RI [ script
.RI [ argument ...]]
.br
.B shit
.B \-c
.I command
.RI [ argument ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B shit
is a fast POSIX and bash compatible shell. An interactive prompt is run when
standard input is a terminal and no script is given. A script file named on the
command line is run instead, or a command string is run when it is given with
.BR \-c .
.SH MOODS
The shell runs under one of three moods. The mood sets how strict the run is.
The default
.B shit
mood is the strictest bash superset, and a questionable construct is warned on
through the analysis stage. The
.B bash
mood runs the bash extensions with the analysis stage off. The
.B sh
mood behaves like dash. The nounset, pipefail, and failglob strictness, the
analysis stage, and the parser features are all driven by the mood.
.PP
A binary named or symlinked to
.BR sh ", " dash ", or " bash
is matched to the corresponding mood, and diagnostics are turned off. The mood
is changed at runtime by the
.B set --mood
builtin, and a
.B set --mood
inside the rc sticks for the session. An explicit
.BR "set -u" ", " "set -o pipefail" ", or " "set -o failglob"
is the script's own ask and survives a later mood switch.
.SH OPTIONS
.SS Mood and startup
.TP
.BR \-M ", " \-\-mood =\fINAME\fR
The runtime mood is selected, one of
.BR shit ", " bash ", or " sh .
.TP
.BR \-L ", " \-\-init\-moods =\fILIST\fR
The startup files for each listed mood are sourced, in order. The list is given
comma separated or by repeating the flag. The
.B shit
mood reads /etc/shitrc and ~/.shitrc, the
.B bash
mood reads the bash rc and its completion, and the
.B sh
mood reads the file named by ENV. The list defaults to the value of
.BR \-\-mood .
.TP
.BR \-I ", " \-\-mimicry
A script whose shebang names a shell shit can emulate is run in-process in the
matching mood. The in-process run keeps the diagnostics and saves the launch of
the real shell.
.TP
.B \-\-dumb
The flags
.BR "\-\-mood sh \-T \-\-no\-diagnostics"
are applied together.
.TP
.BR \-p ", " \-\-privileged
Every startup config file is skipped. The flag is turned on automatically in the
setuid or setgid case.
.TP
.B \-\-clean
A clean shell is started. No startup file is read in any mood, and PATH is set
to a minimal default.
.TP
.BI \-\-rcfile= FILE
FILE is sourced as the interactive rc. The shit mood sources it in place of
/etc/shitrc and ~/.shitrc, and the bash mood in place of ~/.bashrc.
.TP
.B \-\-posix
POSIX mode is selected, the same as
.BR "\-\-mood sh" .
A terminal that re-execs the shell with
.B \-\-posix
to inject its integration through the ENV file is honored.
.SS Diagnostics
.TP
.BR \-W ", " \-\-force\-warnings
The analysis stage is kept, but every error is reported as a warning and the run
proceeds.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-diagnostics
The analysis stage is skipped. No warning or pre-run diagnostic is reported.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-init\-diagnostics
Diagnostics and warnings are suppressed only while the startup files source,
then restored for the prompt. The flag pairs with
.BR \-W .
.TP
.B \-\-list\-diagnostics
The shellcheck-style checks the analysis stage reports are listed, then the
shell exits.
.TP
.BR \-T ", " \-\-no\-completion
Interactive tab completion and ghost-text are disabled.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-syntax\-highlighting
The syntax coloring and the ghost suggestion are disabled, and tab completion
still works.
.TP
.B \-\-enable\-shitbox
The bundled shitbox utility names such as
.BR ls ", " mkdir ", and " cp
resolve directly as commands, the same as
.BR "set \-o shitbox" .
.SS POSIX
.TP
.BR \-c " \fICOMMAND\fR"
Commands are read from the string COMMAND.
.TP
.BR \-i ", " \-\-interactive
Interactive mode is forced.
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-stdin
Commands are read from standard input.
.TP
.BR \-e ", " \-\-error\-exit
The shell exits on the first failing command.
.TP
.BR \-f ", " \-\-no\-glob
Pathname expansion is disabled.
.TP
.BR \-u ", " \-\-no\-unset
An unset variable is treated as an error.
.TP
.BR \-C ", " \-\-no\-clobber
An existing file is not overwritten through a plain redirection.
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-no\-exec
The script is parsed without being run.
.TP
.BR \-t ", " \-\-one\-command
A single command is read and run, then the shell exits.
.TP
.BR \-x ", " \-\-xtrace
Each command is printed after expansion.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Each line is printed as it is read.
.TP
.BR \-a ", " \-\-export\-all
Every later assignment is marked for the environment.
.TP
.BR \-l ", " \-\-login
The shell runs as a login shell.
.SS Information
.TP
.B \-\-help
The help message is displayed, then the shell exits.
.TP
.B \-\-version
The version and notices are displayed, then the shell exits.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-short\-version
The short version is displayed, then the shell exits.
.SS Debugging
.TP
.BR \-A ", " \-\-show\-ast
The syntax tree is printed before each command runs.
.TP
.BR \-E ", " \-\-show\-exit\-code
The exit code is printed after each command.
.TP
.BR \-R ", " \-\-show\-lexed\-words
The escape bitmap is printed after each parsed command.
.TP
.B \-\-show\-optimizer\-state
The analysis prepass decisions are traced, and a located line is printed to
standard error for every node the analysis stage eliminated, then a final
summary.
.TP
.B \-\-show\-stats
Per-command statistics are printed.
.TP
.B \-\-show\-memory
A memory report is printed at exit.
.TP
.BI \-X " LEVEL" "\fR, \fB\-\-debug\-logging=" LEVEL
Internal logging is enabled at LEVEL, one of
.BR info ", " debug ", or " all .
The flag is compiled in only in a debug build.
.TP
.BI \-\-debug\-logging\-file= FILE
The debug log is appended to FILE in place of standard error.
.SH BASH SYNTAX
The bash language beyond POSIX sh is accepted in every mood but sh. The forms
below are the additions, with the traps a compatible reimplementation has to get
right.
.SS Arrays
.TP
.B Indexed
An array is built with a=(x y z), an element is set with a[2]=z, and more are
appended with a+=(w). ${a[i]} reads an element through an arithmetic subscript,
${a[@]} and ${a[*]} list the elements, ${#a[@]} counts them, and ${!a[@]} lists
the indices. A negative index counts from the end. A gap left by a[5]=q makes a
sparse array whose ${!a[@]} skips the holes.
.TP
.B Associative
An associative array is declared with declare \-A m, then set with m[key]=v and
read with ${m[key]}. ${!m[@]} lists the keys, and unset 'm[key]' removes one
entry.
.TP
.B "The quoting trap"
"${a[@]}" keeps each element a separate field, while "${a[*]}" joins them on the
first byte of IFS. An inner ${a[*]} inside ${x[@]+"${a[*]}"} still joins on IFS.
A read of ${a[@]} under set \-u raises an error when a is unset.
.SS Conditionals and arithmetic
.TP
.B "[[ ... ]]"
The test command takes ==, !=, the numeric \-eq family, the file tests including
\-nt and \-ot, && and ||, and =~ for a POSIX regex that fills BASH_REMATCH. The
right side of == is a glob when it is bare and a literal when it is quoted, and
=~ splits the same way. && and || short\-circuit, so a dead branch that holds a
malformed regex is never compiled.
.TP
.B "(( ... )) and $(( ... ))"
Arithmetic takes the C operators, ++ and \-\-, **, the ternary, the comma, the
assignment operators, and a based literal such as 16#ff. A name is re\-evaluated
as an expression, so a[b[c]] resolves c, then b, then a. An empty (( )) exits 1,
while $(( )) yields its value.
.SS Parameter expansion
.TP
.B Substring
${v:offset:length} cuts a substring. A negative offset is written with a leading
space, ${v: \-3}. Without the space ${v:\-3} is the default\-value form. A
negative length stops that many characters from the end.
.TP
.B Replacement
${v/pat/rep} replaces the first match and ${v//pat/rep} every match, anchored by
/# at the front and /% at the end. An & in the replacement stands for the
matched text, and \\& is a literal &.
.TP
.B "Case and transform"
${v^^} and ${v,,} change the case of every character, ${v^} and ${v,} the first,
each with an optional pattern. The ${v@Q}, @E, @A, @P, and @a transforms quote,
expand, render, and report the value.
.TP
.B Indirection
${!ref} reads the variable that ref names. ${!pre*} and ${!pre@} list the names
that start with pre.
.SS Word generation
.TP
.B "Brace expansion"
{a,b,c} lists words, {1..10} and {a..z} count a range, {1..10..2} adds a step,
and {001..10} pads the width. Braces nest and multiply. A lone {a} stays
literal.
.TP
.B Quoting
$'...' reads the C escapes \\n, \\t, \\xHH, and \\OOO. $"..." marks a string
for translation, the plain double quote when no catalog is present.
.TP
.B "Redirection and substitution"
&> and &>> send both output streams to a file, and |& pipes both. <(cmd) and
>(cmd) are process substitutions on a /dev/fd path, and <<< is a here\-string
that appends one newline.
.TP
.B Globbing
shopt \-s extglob turns on ?(), *(), +(), @(), and !(), and shopt \-s globstar
turns on **. dotglob, nullglob, and failglob change how a leading dot, a
non\-match, and a failed match are treated. In the default mood a non\-matching
glob and a glob in command position are fatal, and a compatibility mood warns.
.SS Builtins and pitfalls
.TP
.B Attributes
declare, local, typeset, and readonly take \-a, \-A, \-i, \-r, and \-x. printf
takes \-v to assign its result, and mapfile and readarray with \-t read the
lines of the input into an array.
.TP
.B "Pipeline status"
Under set \-o pipefail the pipeline reports the rightmost failing stage, and the
default mood turns pipefail on. PIPESTATUS holds every stage's status in either
case.
.TP
.B "Word splitting"
An unquoted $@ or $* splits on IFS. "$@" keeps the parameters apart, and "$*"
joins them on the first byte of IFS. A run of a non\-whitespace IFS character
makes an empty field, and a run of whitespace collapses.
.TP
.B read
read \-r keeps a backslash literal. A plain read treats a trailing backslash as
a line continuation.
.SH LINE EDITING
The interactive line editor starts in emacs mode. A vi-style modal editor is
selected by
.B set \-o vi
and the emacs default is restored by
.BR "set \-o emacs" .
In vi mode each line begins in insert mode. Escape enters command mode. Command
mode provides the motions, the operators with counts, the named registers, the
change repeat, and a visual selection. The visual selection is charwise from
.B v
and whole lines from
.BR V .
The last edit is undone by
.B u
in command mode and by
.B Ctrl\-_
in either mode. The undone edit is redone by
.BR Ctrl\-^ ,
or by
.B Ctrl\-R
in command mode. The incremental history search is opened by
.B Ctrl\-R
in insert mode and by the
.B /
key in command mode. Enter accepts the highlighted match into the line and
leaves the search without running it. Ctrl\-G cancels the search, and the line
is restored to its state from before the search began. The colon key opens an
ex command. The commands
.BR q ", " q! ", " wq ", " wq! ", " x ", and " quit
exit the shell. The cursor shape tracks the submode, a bar in insert, a block in
command, and an underline in visual or while an operator waits for its motion.
In command mode the arrow keys step between the buffer rows and do not recall
history. The insert-mode arrows still recall it. With an operator pending, Up or
Down acts on the current line together with the line above or below, the
linewise dk and dj.
.PP
A block selection is entered with
.B Ctrl\-V
in command mode, a column rectangle across several lines. The keys
.BR d " and " x
delete the rectangle, and
.BR I ", " c ", or " C
insert the typed text at the left column of every selected line, so several
lines are indented at once. The arrows and
.B h j k l
move within the rectangle.
.PP
A multi-cursor edit is entered with
.B Ctrl\-V
in emacs mode and selects nothing. A cursor sits at the same column on every
spanned line, and
.BR Up " or " Down
grows the span by one line. A typed character is inserted at every cursor at
once, and Backspace erases at every cursor. The edit is left with
.BR Ctrl\-G .
.SH RESCUE
When a flag in SHIT_FLAGS or in the argument list fails to parse and standard
input is a terminal, the login shell will enter rescue.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B SHIT_FLAGS
The default flags are applied before the command line. A flag on the command
line still wins. The recommended value is
.BR "\-W \-I \-\-init\-moods=shit,bash" .
.TP
.B SHIT_HISTORY
The command history file, ~/.shit_history by default.
.TP
.B SHIT_DIRECTORY_HISTORY
The frecency store the z builtin ranks, ~/.shit_directory_history by default.
.TP
.B SHIT_CALC_HISTORY
The interactive calc REPL history file, ~/.shit_calc_history by default.
.TP
.B ENV
The startup file sourced in sh mood.
.TP
.B PATH
The colon\-separated command search path. The \-\-clean flag resets it to a
minimal default.
.TP
.B HOME
The home directory. It is read by tilde expansion and by the default rc and
history paths.
.TP
.B PWD
The current working directory, maintained by cd and z.
.TP
.B OLDPWD
The previous working directory, set by cd and z. cd \- returns to it.
.TP
.B SHELL
The path to the shell, set from the environment, or to the running binary when
it is unset.
.TP
.B SHLVL
The shell nesting depth, read from the environment, incremented, and set back so
a child shell counts one deeper.
.TP
.B CDPATH
The colon\-separated search path cd consults for a relative operand.
.TP
.B IFS
The field separator for word splitting and the join of $*, a space, a tab, and a
newline by default.
.TP
.B "COLUMNS, LINES"
The terminal width and height, set for an interactive shell from the terminal
size.
.TP
.B PROMPT_COMMAND
A command run before each interactive prompt is drawn.
.TP
.B TERM
The terminal type, read to decide whether color is supported.
.TP
.B MANPATH
The manual search path, read by completion to offer a subcommand and an option
from the pages.
.TP
.B PIPESTATUS
The indexed array of the exit status of each stage of the last pipeline.
.TP
.B REPLY
The line read by read when no name is given, and the line the select loop
records.
.TP
.B "OPTIND, OPTARG"
The option index and the option argument getopts maintains as it walks the
positional parameters.
.TP
.B TIMEFORMAT
The format the time builtin prints its report in.
.TP
.B PS1
The primary prompt template, rendered before each interactive command. A default
template is supplied when it is unset.
.TP
.B PS0
The prompt rendered and printed after a command line is read and before it runs,
empty by default.
.TP
.B PS2
The continuation prompt default, "> ", carried for compatibility.
.TP
.B PS3
The prompt the select loop prints, "#? " by default.
.TP
.B PS4
The prefix the set \-x trace prints, "+ " by default. The first character is
repeated once per enclosing subshell.
.TP
.B SHIT_VERSION
The shell version, in the major.minor.patch\-extra form such as 0.0.8\-beta.
.TP
.B SHIT_COMMIT
The commit the binary was built from, <no git> when none was recorded.
.TP
.B SHIT_BUILD_MODE
The build mode of the binary, one of dbg, rel, or cov.
.TP
.B SHIT_OS
The host the binary was built on, the distribution and kernel identification.
.TP
.B SHIT_GIT_BRANCH
The branch around the working directory, read from .git without forking git.
The short commit hash is read on a detached head, and an empty value outside a
repository. A stored assignment wins.
.TP
.B NO_COLOR
Color is turned off in the prompt and the diagnostics when the variable is set.
.TP
.B SHIT_ANSI_*
A color escape is provided under each of these names so a prompt template
carries an attribute without an escape byte. The recognized colors are BLACK,
RED, GREEN, YELLOW, BLUE, MAGENTA, CYAN, and WHITE, each also with a BRIGHT_
prefixed high\-intensity form, along with the attributes BOLD, DIM, and RESET.
The names resolve in every mood. A recognized name reads back empty when color
is off, the way NO_COLOR and a redirected prompt turn the escapes off, so the
prompt stays plain. A stored assignment to one of the names wins over the
provided escape.
.TP
.B "RANDOM, SRANDOM, SECONDS, LINENO, EPOCHSECONDS, EPOCHREALTIME"
These resolve on each read. RANDOM and SRANDOM give a fresh random value,
SECONDS counts the seconds since the shell started, LINENO gives the line of the
current command, and EPOCHSECONDS and EPOCHREALTIME give the wall clock time in
seconds. They resolve in every mood but sh.
.TP
.B "BASHPID, PPID, UID, EUID, GROUPS, HOSTNAME, HOSTTYPE, MACHTYPE, OSTYPE"
These describe the running process and the host, resolved on each read. BASHPID
is the process id, PPID is the parent, UID and EUID are the real and the
effective user, GROUPS is the real group, and HOSTNAME, HOSTTYPE, MACHTYPE, and
OSTYPE name the host and the platform. They resolve in every mood but sh.
.TP
.B "SHELLOPTS, BASH_SUBSHELL, BASH_ARGV0, BASH_EXECUTION_STRING, BASH_MONOSECONDS"
These report shell state on each read. SHELLOPTS lists the enabled set \-o
options, BASH_SUBSHELL counts the subshell depth, BASH_ARGV0 is the shell name,
BASH_EXECUTION_STRING is the argument of \-c, and BASH_MONOSECONDS is a
monotonic millisecond counter. They resolve in every mood but sh.
.TP
.B "FUNCNAME, BASH_SOURCE, BASH_LINENO, BASH_COMMAND"
These trace the running code. FUNCNAME names the function in progress,
BASH_SOURCE is the file it was read from, BASH_LINENO is the line of the call,
and BASH_COMMAND is the command being executed. The array forms give the whole
call stack. They resolve in every mood but sh.
.TP
.B BASH_REMATCH
The indexed array of the groups the last [[ ... =~ ... ]] match captured.
.TP
.B "BASH, BASH_VERSION, BASH_VERSINFO"
A bash identity is advertised under these names so a bash rc detects it. They
are seeded only in the bash mood. BASH is the path to the shell, BASH_VERSION is
the version string, and BASH_VERSINFO is its indexed components.
.TP
.B "COMP_WORDS, COMP_CWORD, COMP_LINE, COMP_POINT, COMP_WORDBREAKS, COMPREPLY"
A programmable completion function reads these and writes COMPREPLY. COMP_WORDS
holds the words on the line, COMP_CWORD is the index of the word under the
cursor, COMP_LINE is the whole line, COMP_POINT is the cursor offset, and
COMP_WORDBREAKS is the characters that split a word.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/shitrc
The system rc the shit mood sources.
.TP
.I ~/.shitrc
The user rc the shit mood sources.
.TP
.I ~/.shit_history
The default command history file.
.TP
.I ~/.shit_directory_history
The default frecency store for the z builtin.
.TP
.I ~/.shit_calc_history
The default history file for the interactive calc REPL.
.SH SHITBOX
The
.B shitbox
builtin hosts a set of small bundled coreutilities, so a system with only a
compiler can run a configure and a make under shit.
.B "shitbox ls"
runs the bundled ls. A bundled utility is tried first, and a name with no
matching utility falls back to a shell builtin of that name, so
.B "shitbox echo"
runs the echo builtin. With the
.B \-\-enable\-shitbox
flag or
.B "set \-o shitbox"
the utility names resolve directly as commands without the prefix. A builtin
still wins over a utility, and a utility wins over a program on PATH. A binary
whose name is a utility, such as a symlink named ls, acts as that utility, and
the utility's own flags reach its parser. A symlinked
utility prints the shit version on \-\-version, so the binary behind the name is
visible, and its help names the shit shell.
.B "shitbox \-\-assimilate DIR"
installs one such symlink per utility into DIR. In the default shit mood a bare
utility name also falls back to the bundled utility when PATH holds no binary of
that name, so a missing system coreutil is filled in. A PATH binary still takes
precedence.
.TP
.B calc
The bundled calc utility evaluates each argument as an arithmetic expression and
prints the value of the last one, with the same operators and located errors the
shell arithmetic uses. In the default mood the value is computed in 128 bits, so
a result wider than a signed 64-bit integer prints in full, while the Bash and
POSIX moods keep the 64-bit wrap. With no expression on a terminal, or with
.BR \-i ,
expressions are read and evaluated interactively through the line editor, with
the shell completion and the highlighter turned off and the history kept in
~/.shit_calc_history. An interactive line of the form name=value binds the
variable to its right-side expression unevaluated, recomputed lazily on each
later read, and an assignment inside an expression, such as
.BR "(x = 5) + 1" ,
returns its value. A calc binary on PATH is preferred, so the bundled utility
runs only when PATH holds none, unless the shitbox applet mode is on.
.SH SHIT BUILTINS
These builtins are unique to shit and have no counterpart in bash or dash.
.TP
.B bench
Each command is run repeatedly as a measured child, and a summary of the wall
time, the peak resident set, and the available perf counters is printed as mean,
standard deviation, and range. With more than one command, each later command is
printed against the first as a relative speed.
.TP
.B z
The shell changes to a frequently visited directory ranked by a frecency store
at ~/.shit_directory_history. The store weights each directory by its visit
count and how recently it was seen. The operands join into one query, and a
directory
is matched by case insensitive substring.
.SH EXIT STATUS
The shell exits with the status of the last command it ran. A usage error such
as an unknown flag in a non-interactive run exits with status 2.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR bash (1),
.BR dash (1),
.BR sh (1),
.BR fish (1),
.BR busybox (1)
